#2023GM Q35

Can even occur years after treatment is completed.
They are systemic inflammatory reactions.
Underlying mechanisms are not known.
Type 1: (aka T1R, RR)

  • usually a clinical diagnosis. No risk factors have been identified. Basically, it's like an idiosyncratic reaction.
  • appears to result from spontaneous enhancement of cellular immunity and delayed-type hypersensitivity to M. leprae antigens
  • Usually occurs in borderline disease (BT-BL)
  • Induration, swelling or erythema of previous lesions.
  • Pain or tenderness of nerves AND even loss of nerve function.
  • Natural course is several months.
    Type 2: (aka erythema nodosum leprosum or ENL)
  • Sudden eruption of numerous painful nodules.
  • May rupture and discharge pus but they contain only dead bacteria and neutrophils -> sterile on culture.
  • Biopsy of lesions will show polymorph -> diagnostic of type 2 reactions. (polymorphs not present in other lepromatous lesions).
  • Lepromatous disease.
  • Last for a few days; new crops of lesions may appear.
  • Systemic involvement +
    • High fever
    • tender lymphadenopathy
    • orchitis
    • iridocyclitis
    • muscle tenderness
  • Lucio phenomenon: very rare; occurs in Mexicans. Necrotising punched punched out ulcers. Can be life threatening.

Both share symptoms of neuritis, arthritis, iritis and nasopharyngeal symtoms.
Can lead to severe nerve injury with subsequence paralysis and deformity.

Clofazimine causes a copper (red and dark skin and hair) pigmentation, particularly on areas exposed to light starting during the first 10 weeks of treatment. This is reversible but takes several months. Also causes icthyosis.

  • prolonged APTT found on routine tests (antiphospholipid antibodies can prolong APTT without causing bleeding)

Von Willebrand disease

Inadequate vWF activity - either decreased quantity or function.

●Type 1 is due to a quantitative reduction in von Willebrand factor (VWF) protein (both concentration and activity are decreased). - 85% of patients
●Type 2 is due to dysfunctional VWF.
●Type 3 is due to absent or severely reduced VWF (a severe quantitative reduction). - most severe bleeding
Type 1 and 2 - mild to moderate bleeding;
type 2 and 3 - severe bleeding;

Affected females (adults) are usually symptomatic. Males and children may not have been exposed to sufficient hemostatic challenges to bring them to medical attention.

vWF levels increase with age.

vWF is produced mainly by endothelial cells.
It mediates platelet adhesion and aggregation; and also transports factor VIII (eight) - same factor as haemophilia

half life of vWF = 16 hours;
vWF is increased in inflammation, malignancy and #pregnancy.

commonest inherited bleeding disorder. #autosomalDominant
Haemorrhages are muscle haematoma are generally rare, except in complete lack of vWF.
Patients can present at any age;

[!TIP]
Think of vWD as a disease that's present but usually asymptomatic unless unmasked by some event (either trauma, antiplatelet medication, menstrual bleeding etc)

vWD occurs from deficiency, poor function or complete lack of vWF.
Women are more affected than men for a given vWF level.

Ix: PFA-100 - a test of platelet function - is abnormal.
factor VIII (eight) levels are low.
APTT may be prolonged.
vWF levels are low.
Platelet count is usually normal.

Management:
DDAVP releases vWF from endothelial cells 30 minutes after IV infusion. Works for type 1 vWD where there is only partial quantitative deficiency.

Acquired haemophilia

Acquired factor deficiency -> usually due to acquired factor inhibition.
Commonest such disease is Acquired factor eight (VIII) deficiency -> "acquired haemophilia A".

Predisposing factors : cancer, autoimmune syndrome or postpartum.
Presentation: haemarthrosis is rare. Patients will come with subcutaneous, retroperitoneal or intramuscular bleeding and prolonged APPT.

Management

Recombinanct factor VIII Or "bypassing product".
Acquired factor V inhibitor -> platelet transfusion or bypassing product.
Other inhibitors -> replace with factors concentrate if inhibitor concentraion is below 5 BU. (i.e plasma, PCC etc).

Bypassing agents:
Bypassing agents – These are clotting factor products that contain activated factor VIIa, which bypasses the function of factors VIII and IX in the clotting cascade. Dosing is similar to people with hemophilia and inhibitors, as discussed separately.

FEIBA (factor VIII inhibitor bypassing activity) – This is a PCC from plasma that contains factor VIIa along with factors II, IX, and X (table 3). (See "Treatment of bleeding and perioperative management in hemophilia A and B", section on 'Bypassing products (rFVIIa products or FEIBA)'.)

-Recombinant activated factor VII (rFVIIa) – There are two brands with different dosing and indications. (See "Recombinant factor VIIa: Administration and adverse effects", section on 'Available products and their properties'.)

Delerium


Essential components for diagnosis:

  1. Altered cognition - see below for features
  2. Disturbance of conciousness - ?Objective reduction in GCS

How to remember features:
(mnemonic: cognition = input + process + output)
1. input - hallucinations, unable to maintain attention etc.
2. process - delusions, orientation, memory problems
3. output - language

DSM criteria

Disturbance in attention: reduced ability to focus / sustain / shift attention.
Acute onset: hours to days and fluctuates.
Disturbance in cognition :

  • Deficits of Memory, orientation, language and perception.
    There may be hypo / hyperactivity and increased sympathetic activity.
    emotional disturbances : fear, depression, euphoria etc.

Dementia

Defined by the presence of :

[!TIP] Features of dementia

This man can't figure out how he got came to this room (memory), can't find the words to ask someone why (language), can't figure out what to do to get out of it (executive planning), is disoriented within the room (visuospatial) and is unable to open the door (apraxia)

3 key features of dementia:

  1. acquired loss of higher mental function: (i.e 'lower' function - respiration, autonomic function, cvs are stable).
    1. Affects two or more domains which constitute higher mental function
      1. Language
      2. Memory
      3. Executive function - ?planning ahead
      4. visuospatial function
      5. apraxia

        1. Apraxia (Greek 'praxis' means "do") is the loss of ability to execute or carry out skilled movement and gestures, despite having the physical ability and desire to perform them. Apraxia results from dysfunction of the cerebral hemispheres of your brain, especially the parietal lobe (which his involved with movement coordination and processing sensations such as taste, hearing, and touch) - Source

        2. A dementia patient can't "show me how you brush your teeth"
  2. Sufficient severity to cause significant social or occupational impairment
  3. Being chronic and stable - unlike delerium
